cs.IT, cs.COMM, cs.GR, cs.LG, cs.SY

Reasoning: The paper deals with optimizing constellations over a single-input, single-output Rayleigh fading channel, which is a problem in information theory and communication theory. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.COMM (Communications and Networking) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also involves the construction of rotation matrices, which is a problem in geometry and topology, making cs.GR (Computational Geometry) a likely sub-category as well. The introduction of a new notion of diversity and a local variant of the minimum product distance suggests that the paper may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) or cs.SY (Systems and Control).
